{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T21:02:55.362372+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 66 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 79 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":79,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":66,"completed_with_unit_data":66,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":28,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2603,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 66 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -26.0%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":489,"p25":-0.4831,"median":-0.2603,"p75":-0.0375},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.0569,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 66 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +5.7%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":66,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":66,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.2339,"mean":0.1378,"median":0.0569,"p25":-0.083,"p50":0.0569,"p75":0.2649,"p10":-0.1916,"p90":0.5261},"median_actual_dollars":244737.23},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~117 hours per plumbing unit","value":117.1266,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 117.1 hrs/unit (P25 100, P75 138). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 100 and 138 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":66,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":123.1238,"median":117.1266,"p25":99.9998,"p50":117.1266,"p75":137.7556,"p10":79.3665,"p90":159.121,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.6%","value":0.3865,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.6%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":66,"p25":0.3159,"median":0.3865,"p75":0.4542},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$44.46/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":44.46,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $44.46/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":30.9591,"loaded_wage_median":44.46,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4236},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.6% median)","value":-0.1558,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.6%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":621,"min":-0.9914,"max":4.6293,"mean":-0.0963,"median":-0.1558,"p25":-0.4104,"p50":-0.1558,"p75":0.0916,"p10":-0.5997,"p90":0.4348},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":66,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":123.1238,"median":117.1266,"p25":99.9998,"p50":117.1266,"p75":137.7556,"p10":79.3665,"p90":159.121,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":66,"min":359.0298,"max":11628.9416,"mean":3666.2705,"median":3642.2643,"p25":2917.0449,"p50":3642.2643,"p75":4200.984,"p10":1960.7734,"p90":5021.6519,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":66,"min":1219.6971,"max":9672.2479,"mean":3805.3469,"median":3794.3763,"p25":2926.6184,"p50":3794.3763,"p75":4462.0725,"p10":2097.0736,"p90":5180.3604,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":66,"min":7181.5,"max":41985.5421,"mean":16067.3274,"median":16188.1257,"p25":12863.6377,"p50":16188.1257,"p75":18654.3662,"p10":10192.3323,"p90":20919.7505,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":66,"min":0.0157,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2298,"median":0.2248,"p25":0.2057,"p50":0.2248,"p75":0.2622,"p10":0.185,"p90":0.2865,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":66,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3209,"mean":0.2366,"median":0.2348,"p25":0.2166,"p50":0.2348